      • length

        public static float length(float[] v)
        Calculates the length, or magnitude.

        This is useful for vectors of arbitrary dimensions and quaternions.

        The original array is not modified.

        Parameters:
        v - Array of scalars, with at least 2 entries.
        Returns:
        The result of sqrt(v[0]^2 + v[1]^2 + ... + v[n-1]^2).

      • lengthSquared

        public static float lengthSquared(float[] v)
        Calculates the squared length, or magnitude.

        This is useful for performance reasons (e.g. when comparing vectors or quaternions), because it avoids expensive sqrt computations.

        The original array is not modified.

        Parameters:
        v - Array of scalars, with at least 2 entries.
        Returns:
        The result of v[0]^2 + v[1]^2 + ... + v[n-1]^2.

      • lerp

        public static float[] lerp(float[] s,
                           float[] e,
                           float t)
        Linearly interpolates the values in arrays of arbitrary dimensions, calculated as: 
         lerp(s, e, t) = [(1 - t) * s] + [t * e]
        where s is the starting position, e is the ending position, and t in [0, 1] is the interpolation parameter.

        This implementation:

        • returns s iff t == 0.0
        • returns e iff t == 1.0

        This is useful for vectors and quaternions alike.

        It's the caller's responsibility to ensure that the interpolation parameter is within a valid range.

        The original arrays are not modified.

        Parameters:
        s - The starting position.
        e - The ending position.
        t - The interpolation parameter, t in [0, 1].
        Returns:
        A new array of the same dimension as the inputs containing mid-point values.
